  "prompt": "How are belly buttons formed?",
  "response": "Belly buttons, or navels, are formed as a result of the umbilical cord attachment during gestation. The umbilical cord connects a developing fetus to the placenta, providing nutrients and oxygen from the mother and removing waste products. \n\nHere\u2019s how the formation occurs:\n\n1. **During Pregnancy:** The umbilical cord connects the fetus to the placenta in the mother's womb, facilitating the exchange of necessary substances.\n\n2. **At Birth:** After the baby is born, the umbilical cord is clamped and cut. The remaining stump attached to the baby usually measures about 1-2 inches.\n\n3. **Healing Process:** Over the next few weeks, this stump dries out and eventually falls off. What remains is the scar tissue, which becomes the belly button.\n\nThe appearance of the belly button varies from person to person, being either an \"innie\" (a hollow depression) or an \"outie\" (protruding). The exact shape and size depend on how the skin heals and the muscle structure beneath it.\n\nThere isn't a significant functional purpose for the belly button after birth, but it serves as a reminder of the prenatal connection between mother and child.",
